          "body": "Verse 13 is the chapter's most theologically dense verse. The formulation 'just as He called and they would not listen, so they called and I would not listen' is a precise lex talionis applied to divine-human communication. God had called through the former prophets with the exact content of 7:9-10 — justice, chesed, protection of the vulnerable. The ancestors declined that call at every stage described in 7:11-12. Then the crisis came: Babylon advanced, the land was threatened, the temple was under siege, and the people cried out to God. And He was silent. The symmetry is judicial. This is not an arbitrary divine whim but a built-in covenantal mechanism: the God whose words are refused does not simply continue speaking into the void. His silence in crisis is the acoustic consequence of their silence before the crisis. Unanswered prayer is audited against unobeyed word. Jonathan Edwards observed that when God seems absent in times of desperate need, the question to ask is whether He was present and refused in times of ordinary life. Zechariah 7:13 makes that principle explicit."
